## Conclusion

Global warming poses multifaceted threats to human health and well-being through direct physiological effects, exacerbation of diseases, and socio-economic disruptions. Vulnerable populations—including the elderly, children, the chronically ill, and the poor—bear disproportionate burdens. The evidence underscores the urgency of coordinated global action to mitigate emissions and implement adaptive measures that protect human health.

While uncertainties remain in predicting the precise magnitude and distribution of impacts, the convergence of findings across multiple disciplines and regions affirms that global warming is a significant and growing public health challenge. Policymakers, healthcare systems, and communities must prioritize resilience-building and equitable resource allocation to mitigate these risks.

